SIMPLE: forgo
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forgo
<hw>For*go"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Forwent</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Forgone</conjf>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Forgoing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>forgan</ets>, <ets>forgon</ets>, <ets>forgoon</ets>, AS.
forg⟦amac⟧n, prop., to go past, hence, to abstain from; pref.
<ets>for-</ets> + <ets>g⟦amac⟧n</ets> to go; akin to G.
<ets>vergehen</ets> to pass away, to transgress. See <er>Go</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass by; to leave. See 1st
<er>Forego</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For sith [since] I shall <qex>forgoon</qex> my liberty⟦br⟧
At your request.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And four [days] since Florimell the court <qex>forwent</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to abstain from; to do without; to refrain from; to
renounce; -- said of a thing already enjoyed, or of one within reach, or
anticipated. See 1st <er>forego</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word in spelling has been confused with, and almost
superseded by, <xex>forego</xex> to go before. Etymologically the form
<xex>forgo</xex> is correct.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forgot</ent>⟦br⟧
